SKILL|dogfood|"Exploratory QA of web apps: find bugs, evidence, reports."
STEP|1|Browser toolset must be available (`browser_navigate`, `browser_snapshot`, `browser_click`, `browser_type`, `browser_vision`, `browser_console`, `browser_scroll`, `browser_back`, `browser_press`)
STEP|2|A target URL and testing scope from the user
STEP|3|**Target URL** — the entry point for testing
STEP|4|**Scope** — what areas/features to focus on (or "full site" for comprehensive testing)
STEP|5|**Output directory** (optional) — where to save screenshots and the report (default: `./dogfood-output`)
STEP|6|Create the output directory structure:
STEP|7|Identify the testing scope based on user input.
STEP|8|Build a rough sitemap by planning which pages and features to test:
STEP|9|**Navigate** to the page:
STEP|10|**Take a snapshot** to understand the DOM structure:
STEP|11|**Check the console** for JavaScript errors:
STEP|12|**Take an annotated screenshot** to visually assess the page and identify interactive elements:
STEP|13|**Test interactive elements** systematically:
STEP|14|**After each interaction**, check for:
STEP|15|**Take a screenshot** showing the issue:
STEP|16|**Record the details**:
STEP|17|**Classify the issue** using the issue taxonomy (see `references/issue-taxonomy.md`):
STEP|18|Review all collected issues.
STEP|19|De-duplicate — merge issues that are the same bug manifesting in different places.
STEP|20|Assign final severity and category to each issue.
STEP|21|Sort by severity (Critical first, then High, Medium, Low).
STEP|22|Count issues by severity and category for the executive summary.
STEP|23|**Executive summary** with total issue count, breakdown by severity, and testing scope
STEP|24|**Per-issue sections** with:
STEP|25|**Summary table** of all issues
STEP|26|**Testing notes** — what was tested, what was not, any blockers
STEP|27|**Always check `browser_console()` after navigating and after significant interactions.** Silent JS errors are among the most valuable findings.
STEP|28|**Use `annotate=true` with `browser_vision`** when you need to reason about interactive element positions or when the snapshot refs are unclear.
STEP|29|**Test with both valid and invalid inputs** — form validation bugs are common.
STEP|30|**Scroll through long pages** — content below the fold may have rendering issues.
STEP|31|**Test navigation flows** — click through multi-step processes end-to-end.
STEP|32|**Check responsive behavior** by noting any layout issues visible in screenshots.
STEP|33|**Don't forget edge cases**: empty states, very long text, special characters, rapid clicking.
STEP|34|When reporting screenshots to the user, include `MEDIA:<screenshot_path>` so they can see the evidence inline.
